Akero Therapeutics shares soared on Thursday after Novo Nordisk announced it will acquire the biotech company in a deal valued at up to $5.2 billion, signaling a major expansion of its liver disease portfolio. The Danish drugmaker, best known for its blockbuster diabetes and obesity medications Ozempic and Wegovy, said it will pay $54 per share in cash, with an additional $6 per share contingent on U.S. regulatory approval of Efruxifermin, Akero‚Äôs lead treatment candidate for metabolic dysfunction-associated steatohepatitis (MASH), a form of fatty liver disease linked to obesity. 
Akero‚Äôs stock rose 19% to $55.39 in premarket trading following the announcement. Novo Nordisk said the acquisition strengthens its commitment to building a comprehensive pipeline to address different stages of MASH, an area of growing therapeutic demand.

Delta Air Lines shares surged after the company reported stronger-than-expected third-quarter results and raised its full-year guidance, lifting the entire airline sector. Delta posted adjusted EPS of $1.71 on revenue of $15.2 billion, beating analyst expectations of $1.52 and $15.1 billion, respectively. The airline now expects full-year EPS of $6, above Wall Street‚Äôs $5.80 estimate. Corporate sales increased 8% and premium revenue grew 9% in the quarter, reflecting strong demand across all regions over the past six weeks. 
The stock jumped 6.1% in premarket trading, while peers United Airlines rose 5%, American Airlines climbed 5.1%, and Southwest Airlines gained 2%. CEO Ed Bastian highlighted continued momentum into the final stretch of Delta‚Äôs Centennial year, positioning the airline for strong December-quarter earnings.

Neogen Corporation reported first-quarter results that beat analyst expectations despite ongoing operational challenges. The food and animal safety company‚Äôs shares rose in premarket trading after posting adjusted earnings of $0.04 per share, topping estimates for a $0.07 loss. Revenue came in at $209.2 million, above the $202.4 million consensus but down 3.6% year over year. Core revenue rose 0.3%, while gross margin fell to 45.4% from 48.4%, mainly due to integration costs tied to production relocation. CEO Mike Nassif highlighted renewed focus on execution, innovation, and cost efficiency as Neogen implements cost-cutting measures and uses divestiture proceeds to reduce debt.

Serve Robotics announced a new partnership with DoorDash to roll out its sidewalk delivery robots for food orders, expanding beyond its current collaboration with Uber Eats. The San Francisco-based robotics company said that customers ordering from select restaurants and stores in Los Angeles through DoorDash may now receive their deliveries via Serve robots, according to Reuters and Bloomberg. 
The company plans to expand the program across the United States, leveraging DoorDash‚Äôs position as the leading food delivery platform. The partnership will allow Serve to increase delivery volumes by reaching merchants and customers outside of Uber‚Äôs ecosystem. Serve‚Äôs CEO and co-founder, Ali Kashani, said the collaboration enables the company to enter cities where DoorDash has a dominant presence and better utilize its growing robot fleet.

Helen of Troy reported better-than-expected fiscal second-quarter 2026 results on Thursday, with adjusted earnings and revenue surpassing analyst estimates despite ongoing tariff pressures and softer consumer demand. The branded consumer products designer posted adjusted EPS of $0.59, topping expectations of $0.53, on revenue of $431.8 million, above the $416.8 million consensus. However, both figures were sharply lower year over year, with adjusted EPS down 51% and sales down 9%. 
CFO Brian L. Grass said results were at the high end of guidance and reflected progress despite continued business disruption and cost headwinds. Got diagnosed with ADHD this week.
Made me reflect on a lot of my life...
5 thoughts on how ADHD affected my life (so far)

1: ADHD isn't some "monster in the room", it's just a label for the way my brain is wired + how I act.

The 2 basic biological things are 1) My brain's ability to "tune out" signals is bad (low Dopamine in synapses) so I constantly have a lot of voices/impulses in my head, and 2) My brain's ability send 1 strong signal is bad (low Norepinephrine in synapses) so remembering 1 thing or getting into flow state is difficult.

That means that when I FINALLY DO tune out the noise and get into flow-state, I'm insanely ultra focused, but there are neurological imbalances that make that difficult.

4 things I use AI the most for

1: Multi-Factor Research

Example:

My wife and I wanted to look at some potential apartments/townhomes to rent.  We had a bunch of criteria:
- A 30 min or less drive from a major international airport
- A 10 min drive/train to an excellent gym
A 10-min walk from:
- Coffee Shop
- Coworking space or office
- Grocery Store (mid to nice)
- A Pharmacy
- Slurpees or Icees
- 2+ Heathy fast casual restaurants (Chipotle, Cava, WaBa Grill)
- Park and playground
- Trails or easy walking

That's a long list of very specific things.  I gave that list to Chat GPT-5 deep research.  In 10 minutes, it told me "Here are 8 intersections in Southern California that fit your criteria"

WHAT

5 of them weren't great.  3 were EXACTLY what I wanted.  You can't Google something like that, and a person couldn't do that quickly either!

One example of many super-specific things I wanted an answer to that only a research model could quickly figure out.

Here's how AI can turn the entire internet into usable data

(Tokenization explained in 90 seconds!)

Last week, I explained how AI models scrape and download the text of the entire internet!

Problem: How do we turn that BLOB of text into something an AI can learn from?

Usable data for an AI model has 2 traits:
- A 1-dimensional sequence of symbols (just keeps going left to right)
- A finite set of possible symbols (numbers won't work - infinite increase)

The simplest way to do this is with binary‚Äîjust turn all the text into 0s and 1s. The problem with that is the sequence length.

It turns out, the **LENGTH** of the symbol sequence you feed an AI is a scarce resource. Binary has a VERY simple "vocabulary"‚Äîthe only options are 0 or 1.

But it takes a LOOOOOOOT of 0/1 to represent just 1 word. Simple vocabulary, LONG sequence.

However, if we take common sequences of 0/1 (e.g., the sequence 0000) and make shorthand for them by "minting a new symbol," we can trade away some of the simplicity of our vocabulary to shorten the entire sequence.

The trick is to find the tradeoff point - symbol size and sequence length both slow down model training
- More symbols (Bigger Vocabulary) --> Shorter Sequence
- Less Symbols (Smaller Vocabulary) --> Longer Sequence

GPT-4 was trained on a vocabulary of 100,277 different symbols (tokens).

The process of turning raw data into symbols (tokens) is called Tokenization. Many data scientists have written algorithms/programs to take any dataset and split it into the optimal amount/complexity of tokens to train an AI model.

If you want to see how GPT-4 does this (what Chat GPT was based on until a few weeks ago), here's a great tool: https://t.co/paU5d7gkql.

When you write text to an AI model, it splits it into a whole bunch of specific tokens. It only sees tokens, not words or punctuation. When you get an answer from an AI model, it doesn't know what words it gives you; it just returns a series of tokens that the interface turns into English words, code, or whatever other format you're working with.

That's why any AI you work with (Chat GPT, Claude, Gemini) has "Token Limits"‚Äîhow many symbols does your prompt have, how many symbols does the answer have? Every model limits both inputs and outputs at some number of tokens per minute so their servers don't melt!

I've got a post coming next week on the basic principles of training a neural network with all that tokenized data‚Äîfollow me to see that pop up :)

This is dumb.  2 big reasons:

1: Default to not thinking?

Kaz specifically calls out not using docs or sheets.  He's probably targeting manual data entry or report generation, but most ppl use this stuff for idea capture or quickly testing an idea.

Forcing someone's default to be "Hey AI here's an idea, THINK FOR ME" is destructive.  The default becomes idea -> DON'T THINK -> evaluate an idea.

Would Charlie Munger have defaulted to AI, or defaulted to mental models, then used AI as a quick verification?  I have a hard time imagining Charlie saying "Yes, become an expert in mental models + worldly wisdom, but make your default to have ideas and let something else evaluate them"

Default to first principles, then AI-ify.

Defaulting to an AI to quickly create a report (Perplexity!) instead of by hand is awesome.  Defaulting to it to think about an idea is awful.  Both will happen with this mandate - probably more of the second.

Will create more workslop than actual work.

2: No Concrete Guidance
Toward the bottom, Kaz says people need to think "about how you can build your own agents or save your prompts"
- What does that actually mean?
- HOW do you do that?

Basically every AI tool saves prompts.  Just go into your history and copy/paste.

Agent is a buzzword.  It's any system that does stuff without a human pushing the "execute" button.  ChatGPT is already an agent - it can search the web, do stuff in my calendar, and generate files.

What sorts of agents are there?  Where should I look in my workflow/life for things to automate?  What CAN be automated?  What's WISE to automate?

Zero concrete-ness given.

I showed him EXACTLY what a good hw assignment looks like in my notebook - how to number, when to check, how to rework.

Just saying "Build Agents" probably won't help.  Even a TOUCH of specific guidance or examples from his workflow would do wonders.

5 worst uses of AI (and what to do instead)

1: Life Advice

EVEN IF you give Chat GPT tons of context about you and your life, it gives horrible practical advice.  It will all "melt" into one big soup that's similar to what it tells everyone else.  If you ask it hard questions, it won't push back strategically, it will either try to 1) hype you up or 2) avoid the question with generic slop.

Better: Here's the transcript of all Berkshire Hathaway's shareholder letters.  I'm considering X investment.  Pretend you are Warren Buffet.  What should I do and why?

This helps the AI not "melt" into a compilation of the internet - it solves a specific problem with specific parameters.  (Credit Sam Parr for inspiration)

How to find places to use AI in your business

(5 step checklist you can do right now!)

Steps 1-4 don't involve AI.

DO NOT SKIP THEM.

AI is pointless unless you apply it well.

1: List out your process

List/map your business (or personal) process - from first contact to a loyal customer/finished task

This is a big job.  Probably 4-10 hrs to do well.  If you don't, you can't make decisions about how to improve that process.

2: Delete dumb stuff

Elon Musk's rule of thumb: If I'm not undoing 20% of my deletions, I haven't deleted enough steps.

ALWAYS ask "Do I ACTUALLY need to do this thing?" - less steps = better.

Optimizing/automating needless steps is pointless.  Once you see the process, trim the fat.

3: Find the bottleneck

Find the step in the process that everyone else is "waiting on".
- You have fulfillment capacity but sales team is maxed out
- You have sales capacity but not enough leads
- Your fulfillment can't keep up with demand
- Churn and New Customers are equal - no growth

Whatever your one bottleneck is should be the ONE THING you consider improving.

20% more leads doesn't matter if your sales team doesn't have enough hours in the day - a 20% improvement into a bottle neck is ZERO NET RESULTS.

Effort on anything other than the bottleneck is TOTALLY WASTED.

4: What resource ENABLES YOU to widen the bottleneck?
Don't have enough leads?  A few tools could widen that:
- YouTube videos
- Google Ads
- Cold Emails
- Flyers
- Billboards

Many ways to widen.  Sounds great, but you need to spend a resource to get those tools.  Usually one of:
- Time
- Money
- Focus
- Human Energy (Emotions, Creativity)

5: How can I create more of that resource?

This is where AI (MIGHT) come into play.

If your crunch is time, how can you re-allocate existing time?  That's the best option and it doesn't require AI.

If not, NOW find the least valuable uses of human time in your process.  Then Google "How to use AI to [task]".

You'll probably find youtube videos, linkedin posts, seminars, websites, etc. - from people who mention "I used AI for (thing)".  If you don't, or those resources lack specificity find an AI person (like me :P) and tell them the specific thing you need automated and ask what tools/processes would do it.

If the upfront investment of building and learning the system frees up the time you need to widen the bottleneck, it's worth every penny.

Personally I think AI has the most potential to give back the resource of focus.  Maximum focus on a bottleneck is a fantastic way to widen it.  AI can automate processes that "mathematically" don't need to be automated, but the return you get from only having to work on ONE THING is massive.

Best uses of AI aren't super complicated or magical, they're just sound business decisions.  If you identify a bottleneck, feel free to send me a DM or comment and ask about specific ways AI could widen it!

Frame your goals around finding "No" instead of "Yes".

I made 40 cold visits and was discouraged‚Äî70% said no, 30% said maybe.

Then I did the math based on our data: to close 1 deal, I need to hear "no" 146 times.

OH.

Theory on why Disney is so busy now:

The world is flattening, and now everyone wants to go to the "best places."

Tourist traps are dying, but the biggest and best places are thriving:
- Best ski slopes are packed
- Best restaurants are busy
- Best tutors are hired

Six Flags has slashed their ticket costs to near-zero. Annual passes to the entire 40-park chain cost under $100‚Äîabout 60% less, inflation-adjusted, than 25 years ago. NUTS.

We're living in a winner-take-all world, and the world has flattened:
- Social Media = distribution of the best in the market
- Commoditized air travel = accessible for many
- Navigation/Travel Agents = simple to plan + make the trip
- Rising "mid-tier" of countries = disposable income for leisure travel

Disney has spent the last few decades becoming "THE" destination for family leisure travel and, in the last 15 years, adult leisure as well.

Are they destroying goodwill right now? Yeah, big time‚Äînickel/diming, poor guest experience, limited offerings, poor maintenance, and a limited expansion plan relative to Universal.

But it will take at least 10-15 years for any drop in domestic visitors to outpace the massive influx of "flat world" tourism. You're right!  It is WAY busier - thanks to the "winner-take-all" effect

Here's Disney World's annual attendance over the last 30 yrs:
1994: 35 million
2004: 44 million
2014: 51.5 million
2024: 58 million (+66% from 30 years ago!)

Here's why Disney parks are SO busy now compared to "back in your day":

The world is flattening, and now everyone wants to go to the "best places."

Tourist traps are dying, but the biggest and best places are thriving:
- Best ski slopes are packed
- Best neighborhoods/cities are SLAMMED (The Hamptons?)
- Best restaurants are busy
- Best tutors are hired

Six Flags has slashed their ticket costs to near-zero. Annual passes to the entire 40-park chain cost under $100‚Äîabout 60% less, inflation-adjusted, than 25 years ago. NUTS.

We're living in a winner-take-all world, and the world has flattened:
- Social Media = distribution of the best in the market
- Commoditized air travel = accessible for many
- Navigation/Travel Agents = simple to plan + make the trip
- Rising "mid-tier" of countries = disposable income for leisure travel

Disney has spent the last few decades becoming "THE" destination for family leisure travel and, in the last 15 years, adult leisure as well.  It's an international brand.

They're just happily milking their cash cow (Lightning Lanes, price hikes, cost-cutting, maintenance) while they have momentum and managing like the public company they are - tied to the next quarter's results.

Universal is a sleeper pick in this race. They have a higher perceived position within the "theme park community" because of hardcore fan-awareness.  They opened a fantastic 3rd theme park in Orlando this year, though it is slightly lacking in attraction capacity...

If they manage to keep current momentum for a decade-plus (and Disney keeps releasing incredible box office flops like they've been doing), they could eat away enough of Disney's mindshare with the general public to become a genuine equal in themed entertainment.  But that's a longshot.

Here's how AI can download the entire internet!

(Explained in 90 seconds)

Before we can talk to something like ChatGPT, we need a lot of data so the AI knows what it's talking about. Almost every modern AI (Large Language Model) is trained on essentially the entire internet.

How is that possible?

First, millions of CRAWLERS are scraping data off websites every day. The crawlers:

1. Start at one web page.
2. Read (and download) all its data from top to bottom.
3. Save any links they find on the page.

Then, they go to all those links and repeat the process. If you strategically position crawlers at many different "seed pages" across the web, you can get a representative sample of the entire internet!

Some nonprofit organizations, like Common Crawl, scrape data from 3-5 BILLION pages a month, then put all the data online to download for FREE!

Problem: That's a TON of data.

Solution: FILTER it!
‚ûû Remove "bad" URLs (Malware, Adult Sites)
‚ûû Extract JUST the text (No code/metadata)
‚ûû Filter the languages
‚ûû Many more technical steps (e.g., remove private info)

Now, all that's left is an absolute MOUNTAIN of text. You can find examples of this in places like the "FineWeb" dataset‚ÄîGoogle it! You can download the raw text of (approximately) the ENTIRE INTERNET for free!

How big is the file? 44 Terabytes. Not actually that bad!

So believe it or not, gathering the data of the entire internet into one place is not as hard as you would think.

Problem: A mountain of raw text isn't very useful for an AI...

Solution: Tokenize it!

7 things I've learned after my first 50 (in-person) cold calls!

1: It will always be a little scary

I'm visiting dentists and trying to sell them on using us as one of their suppliers.  On day 1, I was sitting in the parking garage below my first office actually shaking.  I had SO MUCH adrenaline in my system.

I absolutely BOMBED the first visit.  Stumbled over words, nonsense phrases, almost face-planted walking out the door.

The rest of my visits on day 1 were still scary, but I got used to the adrenaline that comes when I walk in the door.

When I did competitive debate, piano performance, sports, heck, even Rubik's Cube competitions, I ALWAYS got hit with adrenaline before the "big moment".  It never went away.  After 50 reps, I think I'll always have adrenaline - I'm not a huge fan of meeting new people lol.  It's going to be a matter of getting used to the adrenaline and being comfortable with the conversations I'm having.

I will say tho, when people go "I could never do cold calls..." THAT WAS ME like 2 months ago.  Now I just sit in my car literally shaking with adrenaline hyping myself up to get out and go visit another office.  It IS hard.  I just go make the calls anyway.

2: They're Skeptical for a Reason

My co-worker (who is way more experienced in Dental Sales) told me about one office he went to where he watched a salesman come in and (after ignoring the receptionist's "not right now") start putting WATER GUNS on the counter and tried to get her to buy water guns.

Like bro what

The receptionist or office manager at a dental office has to deal with SO MANY random things in a day, you walking in SHOULD cause skepticism.  That's THEIR JOB.  Don't resent it.  Understand where they're coming from and adjust to it.

3: I'm there to help

I get over that skepticism realizing "I'm not their enemy.  I want to get to know them and give them a product/experience they will BRAG ABOUT to other dentists."

Once I developed the conviction that if they work with us it will be SO GOOD for them, it stopped feeling like a "fight" and more like HELPING them do something good for both parties.

4: Just Ask Questions

Since I'm there to HELP them, to MEET NEEDS, my job is NOT to walk in and "pitch".

Just ask questions.

Understand their mood.  Understand what sort of business this is.  What their job is.  What their workflow is.  etc.

As I ask genuine questions and follow the conversation instead of some script I came up with, I can literally watch the person I'm talking to relax.  Shoulders drop, deeper breaths, more "human" answers.

I'm not there to "SELL YOU" - I'm there to ask questions and maybe help.  Sometimes they still say no, but that's fine.

5: No is actually a good thing

A big unlock for me was framing my job in terms of No instead of Yes.  I need to hear (based on current estimates) no 149 times before I close one account.  (Which have an average LTV of nearly $1M)

Instead of feeling like a failure every time I hear "no", I should be ENCOURAGED because I'm 1/149th of the way to finding a new account.

If someone says no, it's not personal!
- Maybe they're suddenly slammed and I need to come back later.  Some calls I make and get a no, then I re-visit a couple hrs later and I'm welcomed in!
- Maybe they're having a bad day and are a bit snappy.  That's ok!
- Maybe they just got off the phone with a horrible salesman and don't want to deal with another right now.  That's fine!
- Maybe their business model isn't a fit for our pricing or strategy.  That's great!

If I hear no, move on and either 1) come back later, or 2) accept that this doctor isn't someone I can help.  Go find someone else.

I'm not trying to "convert" everyone.  I'm trying to FIND the right yes.  Hearing no is just the path to get there.

6: Follow-Ups are where the money is

A LOT of people cold-call once.  Very few cold-call twice.  On the second visit when you say something like "I stopped by 2 weeks ago" you can see the surprise on the receptionist's face - "wait you came back?!"

People are SO MUCH MORE WILLING to listen/engage when they realize you actually care about them.  That almost always takes multiple points of personalized contact.  That doesn't mean I suck.  It's just how human relationships work.

7: A Great List has HUGE leverage

As I'm just "doing the thing" and visiting dentist after dentist, I am FEELING how helpful more leveraged strategies are.

If it takes me 5 visits to close an office, and only 40% of offices are worth following up with after each visit, it will take me 98 VISITS to close 1 doctor.  That's a LOT of visits!  I'm only halfway there after a couple weeks of driving around San Diego.

If my list of "cold visits" is a little more enriched, a little warmed up via ads or emails, whatever it takes to bump my success rate from 40% to 50% JUST ON VISIT 1, it only takes me 78 VISITS to close an account.

That's a MASSIVE productivity increase over a year because of a slightly higher percentage conversion at one stage of the process.

So now, on my nights and weekends, I'm learning how to do lead gen/enrichment that leads to booked appointments instead of having to cold source every appt.  It might not work in this business model, but in a future venture I start it will be a VERY useful skill.

Sales is hard work.  Just 3 weeks on the job and I've already learned a ton.  Tons of respect to the masters in the field.

Most people struggle with sales.
To win, turn B2C problems into B2B problems.
B2C problems are:
- Interest-based (How to collect all Gengar Pokemon cards)
- Technology-based (How to use ChatGPT)
- Curiosity-based (How does the NYC subway work?)
- Socially-based (How do I get a date?)
- Convenience-based (How do I get to work faster?)

These are great but hard to SELL because there's no explicit financial return. They're fun, fast, exciting, but there's no ROI.

B2B problems have a clear financial return:
- Make money with ChatGPT (Justifiable expense, but hazy ROI)
- Get your phlebotomist certification and make $25/hr (Investment - unclear timeline, clear ROI)
- Make $1,000 with ChatGPT in 21 days with this business model (Investment - concrete timeline and ROI)

Telling a business owner "You give me $1, I give you $5" is SELLABLE - it's quantifiably good for them. You primarily have to overcome belief in YOU - do they believe you can do this - and then belief in themselves - will this help THEM? If yes, then of course trade $1 for $5.

Solving B2C problems is doable (millions of businesses do it daily), but a harder SALE on average. Frame those problems with:
- a specific timeline
- action
- financial return

to make a more straightforward sale.

Given my strengths in process, systems, operations, and selling a VISION to people who want something USEFUL, I'll be continuing to operate in the B2B problem space wherever possible.

Buffett's Blueprint: How He Started and His Advice for the Next Generation

SHAREHOLDER: 
What first sparked your interest in investing at such a young age, and what advice would you give to a young person that is interested in the stock market? Thank you.

WARREN BUFFETT: 
Well, the interest, I got interested probably when I was about seven or so. I‚Äôd wasted my youth up until then. 

It was a little like W. C. Fields, who said he‚Äôd, they asked him what he‚Äôd, he‚Äôd inherited some money, and they asked him what he‚Äôd done with it. And he said he‚Äôd spent half of it on whiskey, and the rest of it he‚Äôd wasted. (Laughter)

And my dad was in the investment business, a stockbroker. So his office was on the fourth floor of the Omaha Building at 17th and Farnam. And I‚Äôd go down to his office. I had nothing else to do. And I would see these interesting books. And I would read. And Harris, Upham & Co. was on the second floor. They had a board. So I‚Äôd go down there.

The market was open on Saturdays in those days. So I could go down on Saturday. And I saw all these books and all those interesting things. And I probably took out every book in the Omaha Public Library on investing or the stock market by the time I was, you know, 11 or 12. And I got very interested in the New York Stock Exchange.

And I thought, you know, maybe that‚Äôs what I‚Äôd like to do when I grew up. And when I was 11, I bought three shares of stock. And I just was fascinated by it. And then my dad got elected to Congress. So the library even got bigger. And I took out virtually every book. I drew charts. I did all that sort of thing.

And finally, I read a book by Ben Graham, ‚ÄúThe Intelligent Investor,‚Äù when I was at the University of Nebraska, when I was 19. And that just changed my whole framework. So, the advice I would give is to read everything you can. And to start doing it at a very young age. It‚Äôs a huge advantage in almost any field to start when you‚Äôre young. And if it‚Äôs your passion, and you start reading a lot about it when you‚Äôre very young, you‚Äôre going to do well.

I mean, there‚Äôs no secrets in this business that only the priesthood knows, you know. We don‚Äôt go into a temple and look at a lot of secret scrolls that only we get to see. It‚Äôs all out there in black and white. It‚Äôs a simple business. And it requires qualities of character far more than it requires qualities of intellect. I mean, if you‚Äôve got an IQ over 125, you can throw away the rest, or give them to your family or something, and you don‚Äôt need them in investments.

But you do need a certain character that enables you to think independently. And then you have to develop a framework for investment. And I developed that from reading Ben Graham. I didn‚Äôt come up with it myself. It‚Äôs a very simple framework. And then you have to look for opportunities throughout your life that fit that framework. But you won‚Äôt find them every day. You know, you can learn every day, but you can‚Äôt act every day.

I say I read the annual report of the Anheuser-Busch company for 25 years before we invested. And I‚Äôd read Coca-Cola and Gillette and all these other companies long before we invested. If you like the game, you‚Äôll find that a lot like playing bridge or playing baseball. If you don‚Äôt like it, you probably aren‚Äôt going to do that well. But I‚Äôd advise you to start early, read everything in sight, and find a framework that‚Äôs been successful for other people. And there‚Äôs nothing like Graham, in my view. And you‚Äôll have a lot of fun, and you‚Äôll probably make a lot of money. Charlie?

CHARLIE MUNGER: 
Well, I‚Äôm at a slight disadvantage here. Warren became a master of this at a very young age. He had a more respectable career than I did.

A falling market isn‚Äôt disaster, it‚Äôs opportunity arriving in disguise.

Is your favorite company lying to you? They might be‚Ä¶ and it could be perfectly ‚Äúlegal.‚Äù ü§Ø

This is not fear-mongering. It's a harsh lesson from Charlie Munger, Warren Buffett's legendary partner.

His core idea: Accounting should be PESSIMISTIC.

Why? Because optimistic accounting is a public menace. It allows companies to present failure as success.

The Ultimate Example: Enron. Remember them? In the early 2000s, Enron was an energy giant, a Wall Street darling. Then it collapsed into dust, wiping out thousands of investors and employees.

How? They used "generally accepted accounting principles" (GAAP) to basically invent profits out of thin air. They booked revenue for deals that hadn't happened and for contracts that were wildly overvalued.

This is what Munger calls the danger of a system that invites delusion and fraud.

Most CEOs say they ‚Äúcreate shareholder value.‚Äù

But very few actually do it.

Harvard research broke it down into 10 timeless rules.
Follow them, and you get Berkshire-like results. Ignore them, and you risk Enron.

The Boy Wonder and His Trading Machine

In the mid-1980s, Ken Griffin, a precocious 18-year-old at Harvard, was desperate for a satellite dish. While he told the administration it was for the "unlimited selection of TV channels," its true purpose was to beam real-time stock quotes directly into his Cabot House dorm room, turning it into a miniature trading floor. He had already convinced his grandmother, family, and friends to entrust him with $265,000, launching his first venture: Convertible Hedge Fund #1.

While his classmates studied economics, Griffin lived it. He spent hours poring over data, discovering that the market for convertible bonds was filled with pricing errors, inefficiencies he could exploit. He cold-called a broker at First National Bank of Chicago, Saul Golkin, and persuaded him to execute trades for his tiny, dorm-room fund. Griffin was so confident in his analysis that he would buy a bond and short its corresponding stock, a strategy that insulated him from broad market moves.

His system faced its ultimate test on Black Monday, October 19, 1987. As the market went into a free fall and Wall Street veterans were wiped out, Griffin‚Äôs strategy worked flawlessly. While chaos reigned, he was a picture of calm, and his fund produced spectacular positive returns, making his initial investors a stunning $750,000.

News of this wunderkind reached Frank Meyer, a hedge fund pioneer at Glenwood Investment Corp. Intrigued, Meyer gave the 19-year-old his first million-dollar check to manage. A year later, in 1990, Griffin launched his own firm with Meyer's backing, initially called Wellington Partners. He soon renamed it Citadel.

From day one, Griffin's vision was radically different. He wasn't building a boutique fund; he was building a financial institution. He declared, "Every organization has two choices... Grow or die." Instead of hiring Wall Street veterans, he recruited mathematicians, scientists, and even consultants from firms like Boston Consulting Group (BCG). In a move unheard of at the time, he had the BCG team map out every single step of Citadel's investment process into complex flow charts, looking for any possible inefficiency to eliminate or automate. He was building a machine, an "assembly line," as the article calls it, to methodically produce winning strategies.

The machine was tested again a decade later. In 1998, the Russian government defaulted on its debt, causing the collapse of the massive hedge fund Long-Term Capital Management and sending shockwaves through the global financial system. As other funds hemorrhaged cash, Citadel‚Äôs process-driven, risk-managed approach thrived. The firm navigated the turmoil and ended the year with an incredible 30.5 percent return.

The crisis only hardened Griffin's resolve to control his own destiny. Frustrated with the risks posed by relying on Wall Street banks, he hired experts to build his own in-house securities lending and clearing operations, a move that gave Citadel unparalleled independence.

By the age of 32, the boy from the Harvard dorm room was managing over $6 billion. But he was just getting started. His goal wasn't just to be successful, but to build something permanent, the "first great hedge fund shop" that would endure any storm and outlast any single person, himself included.

Stephen Miller gave a speech at Charlie Kirk's memorial today, in Arizona. A divisive, partisan speech, not of peace, but of strife. One that reminds me of a speech made long ago, in another time and place, and the parallels not unintentional.

"It was late in the evening and I was enjoying the rare pleasure of reading a good book. The telephone rang. A voice speaking in breathless haste told me that Horst Wessel had been shot. He was dying.

I did not know Horst Wessel personally. I had heard his name, of course. He was one of the many unknown SA fighters in Berlin who, unnoticed and unknown, fight the battles of the National Socialist movement in the dark streets of the great city.

I had him brought to me. He lay in the hospital, his face pale as death, his eyes closed. His mother sat by his bed. She told me his life story, his hopes for a better world, and how he had tried to save a prostitute he had met on the street. I saw in him an idealistic dreamer, a young man who had devoted his life to the movement.

The doctor told me that he would not live through the night. I stood by his bed and swore a silent oath of vengeance. Horst Wessel died that night.

But he did not die. He lives on in the hearts of thousands of young fighters who, like him, are ready to sacrifice everything for the cause. He has joined the combat group that fights invisibly alongside us. Whenever we sing his song, he is with us.

The red front falls silent when our banners appear. The streets are ours. We march with raised flags, and the song resounds:

"Raise high the flag! The ranks tightly closed! SA marching with quiet, steady step..."

Horst Wessel wrote these words. They were his testament. Now they are the hymn of the German revolution. From a thousand throats they ring out in the night, and the enemy trembles.

In the East End of Berlin, Horst Wessel opened a path through which a brown storm tide poured in unceasingly and conquered the area inch by inch. He was a storm trooper of the soul, a fighter who knew no fear. The communists murdered him, but they could not kill his spirit.

His blood cries out to us from the pavements of Berlin. It demands vengeance. It demands that we carry on his work. Every SA man who falls joins Horst Wessel's combat group. They fight with us, unseen but ever-present.

The banners wave, the trumpets sound, the pipes play, and from a million throats the song of the German revolution resounds:

"Raise high the flag!"

We will not rest until the red flag lies in the dust and the swastika banner flies over a free Germany. Horst Wessel has shown us the way. He has died that we might live."

Raise High the Flag!
A eulogy for Horst Wessel
Josef Goebbels, 27 February 1930

Welcome to the dark side!

What it does affect though, is how you tackle projects- especially the ones I‚Äôm doing in our home. I don‚Äôt struggle with steps or organizing them for clients the same way, but when I‚Äôm working on something outside of my normal day to day projects- it‚Äôs tougher to stay motivated and organized. 

When I get overwhelmed though, the best thing I can do is step back and knock something small off my list. It isn‚Äôt about the end result- it‚Äôs about that bit of dopamine you get checking something off my list. Sometimes I need that more than mediocre progress on a project that takes days or weeks.

That time I broke my foot by shear ‚Äúwrong place, wrong time‚Äù sort of scenario. I had safety boots on, the tile fell just right- full corner of heavy tile right behind the toe box. It was the perfect storm of ‚Äúwhat just happened?!‚Äù 

5 months ago I posted this outtake to just share a little behind the scenes moment from this renovation. I had no idea that it would be viewed millions of times on instagram alone. For a lot of folks- that‚Äôs no big deal- but it was surprising to me. I almost didn‚Äôt share it! 

Most people in construction have injuries from time to time. For all of my health and physical weaknesses- it was actually the first time something happened while I was actually ‚Äúworking‚Äù. I was called every name, some laughed, some appreciated my focus on the job, and a lot were like ‚Äúwait- that‚Äôs an under-reaction in my book!‚Äù

But look- I just wanted to share an inside look at what drives me. When I love something- any obstacle is just not that important. Pain, failure, or being told I can‚Äôt or shouldn‚Äôt do something doesn‚Äôt really factor into it for me. I‚Äôm happy to share my wins and losses, because they are all part of what I love! 

So whether you laugh, criticize, or you‚Äôre cheering me on. I‚Äôm glad you‚Äôre here. I learn from all of it- and learning is ALWAYS my goal!

Autism Awareness Day is every day in our home! 

Ben‚Äôs story isn‚Äôt like a lot of others. Ben has Austism with Regression, which is a different clinical diagnosis to autism itself. Ben developed typically, until 20 months when a switch flipped. His body suffered an ill reaction to a routine medical treatment which caused his immune system to attack itself and eventually caused significant seizures. 

Ben has had a difficult but absolutely beautiful life. We are all better for the journey Ben has taken. He works every day to find his place in our world, and we work every day to enter his world too! He teaches me every single day what love truly is. He teaches me what passion looks like. He inspires me to want more and do more. Our world looks a little different than others, but ya know what? It‚Äôs freaking beautiful!

I am who I am because Ben taught me to be this person. Celebrating a day every year seems so odd, because Ben is infinitely more than the sum of a day. He is a gift every single day, every single hour, every single minute. 

He impacts lives every day and teaches others everything he taught me. You think you know what being strong is? You don‚Äôt until you‚Äôve known Ben! He dreams up ideas and trusts me to make them happen. Now that, is something incredibly beautiful! 

For the last few years, I‚Äôve wanted to find a way to help others in their journey as a family with an autistic person, whether that‚Äôs improving safety, family relations, creating safe spaces for everyone to connect and celebrate their similarities instead of their differences. One day- I truly hope to make that a reality!

Best part of this bathroom renovation has been getting my kids involved! How do y‚Äôall include your kids in learning about your career?! 

For me- they‚Äôve never had a choice. When I started my business they were young, I spent the first several years of their lives as a stay at home mama, and I loved every minute, even when it gave me loads of gray hair! 

When I started TGG, I knew I wanted them to be involved! Getting to included them in this whole process has made it so much more special and so much more meaningful! They aren‚Äôt just hearing about a job, or seeing photos, they‚Äôre watching it happen and playing a part! 

I am living for this!

It‚Äôs been‚Ä¶. Well‚Ä¶ lame. A week or WTH moments sprinkled in with ‚Äúyou‚Äôve got to be kidding me‚Äù‚Ä¶. Anyone else feeling it? Burnout, exhaustion, emotionally constipated, mentally numb. 

Last week, I installed the valves, all went well‚Ä¶ until‚Ä¶ 10 mins after I turned the water back on a pipe above the area I transitioned started to leak. Now- this happens. Our 30 year old copper pipes are slowly getting switched out, and I‚Äôve noticed that leaks always tend to show when you‚Äôve turned the water on after being off for a bit. Small vulnerabilities turn into my problems and it‚Äôs like a needle in a haystack trying to find the issue. 

Thankfully I found it. It could have been worse, I was at it until 11:30 that night though and was totally fried. Once I stopped, I showered and blew dry my hair, and like normal decided to straighten it. Somehow in my exhaustion, I burned my ankle badly. Like a 2X1 inch burn that bordered on a second degree. Annoying, but all good. Cleaned it up, used the special bandages that are perfect for burns and was fine. Barely noticed it the next two days. Until‚Ä¶.

I was heading to bed Wednesday night and the bandage got caught on the sheet, and fully ripped not only the burnt skin off, but also the layer underneath it. That was OMG painful. I almost blacked out, and in my 38 years I‚Äôve never done that. 

It got worse every day, I did all the right things but it‚Äôs not healing. Swelling, pain and all around ouch is putting it so lightly. So- seeing the doctor tomorrow to step up the treatment because it‚Äôs just not healing. 

Sometimes life is like that. You try really hard. You do all the right things, and things just go wrong. So- I‚Äôve been quiet, because honestly I don‚Äôt want to fake it. And I haven‚Äôt really been able to do much since standing makes the injury swell up like a balloon. 

So- to all you folks in the thick of it. I see you. And I‚Äôm praying you get your head out of the weeds too. 

XOXO- Sarah

The JOY in Autism. Here‚Äôs a little inside look at the absolute wonder of being a mom to the sweetest humans imaginable! 

Today is Dinkle‚Äôs birthday. Do you know who Mr Dinkle‚Äôs is?! Well- he‚Äôs a small character in Trolls that Ben absolutely loves. I mean- obsessed. 

In his journey to connect his mind to others, and relate one thing to other things, when he gets a bit obsessed about something, he goes ALL IN. So- when Ben decided that this character that‚Äôs fairly obscure was his favorite, he had to have all the Dinkle‚Äôs characters. There aren‚Äôt many, so mama has made numerous over the years- By the way, I‚Äôm not good at sewing. üòÇ but- he became FAMILY in Ben‚Äôs mind and therefore he needs a birthday! 

So last year we randomly picked a day and that became his birthday, and he celebrated it, and ya know what? He used some of that enthusiasm to better understand dates, times, and now we celebrated Dinkle‚Äôs birthdays every April 16th! For at least 2 months we‚Äôve been discussing what kind of cake Dinkle‚Äôs wanted, and today was finally the day! 

We made that cake, and we sang Happy Birthday and we gave him presents- AKA artwork. We called Dad since he was out of town too! For all of the tough parts of Autism, and there are some tough parts, there are so many more truly beautiful gifts that come with it. Sweet Ben learns in a way all his own, and he does have things that he LOVES that some people may not understand. At times we do things in slow motion, and then at times I swear he is so many steps ahead of me he must be thinking, ‚ÄúMom, CATCH UP!‚Äù 

But- for a child who was non verbal until 6.5, and who has broken EVERY barrier and shattered every glass ceiling others created for him, he is so incredibly positive and happy. It‚Äôs so easy to love every single part of him. When life gives you love, share it. 

So- tomorrow I promise I‚Äôll be back to sharing tool content, but today, I had to give an extra special shout out to Mr Dinkle‚Äôs on his birthday!!

Last word on the Google ruling is that the anti trust legal system not having a method to adjudicate issues of short-lived markets leaves no real option for remedies when the ground shifts.

Any business dynamic can be considered a "market" if you warp the data enough. The court got in trouble when they decided to split "General Search Engines" (GSE) from vertical search like Amazon or Expedia. It's obviously the same function, but that would have meant Google is obviously not a monopolist.

The turn then when GSEs got instant competition from startups like OpenAI should not have been able to happen based on the market dynamics the district court was planning to punish Google for

The GenAI-focused remedies are outside the bounds of the monopoly ruling and I wouldn't be surprised to see several overturned as legislating from the bench

The argument by @dmccabe in The Daily that the MSFT cases in the 90s "helped allow" google to come about is so beyond absurd its not even funny

The legacy of those cases and the legacy of this one are the same. DOJ way overstepped and the courts remedy  impacted exactly nothing about the technical development of US tech companies. 

The MSFT cases extracted rents and turned public opinion but accomplished exactly no actual results in directing market forces of web2.0 companies, just as this case did/is doing nothing to direct the development of Google Search and GenAI companies now

The court doesnt even have the jurisdiction they claim to have regarding the remedies carved out for GenAI and not related to the 'general search' monopoly claim

‚Ä¢ Summer 2020, Portland federal courthouse. Hundreds of federal officers deployed. About 1.6 million dollars in damage. Oversight later criticized deployment readiness. [DHS OIG][OPB][CBS News]

More documented incidents
‚Ä¢ Seattle, WA, Jun‚ÄìJul 2020. CHOP zone shootings and unrest near SPD East Precinct. One teen killed, multiple injured. [Seattle Police Blotter][Seattle Times]
‚Ä¢ Portland, OR, Jan 20, 2021. Inauguration Day vandalism at Oregon Democratic Party HQ. Arrests made. [Reuters][CBS News][The Guardian]

2025. New flashpoints

Designation
On Sept 22, 2025, President Trump signed an order designating Antifa as a domestic terrorist organization. Posted by the White House, entered in the Federal Register, and summarized by the UCSB presidency project. [White House][Federal Register][UCSB Presidency Project]

What the administration is doing now
‚Ä¢ Executive actions. The designation order directs agencies to investigate, disrupt, and dismantle Antifa linked illegal operations. A follow up memo calls for an all of government approach to organized political violence. [White House]
‚Ä¢ DHS posture. DHS highlights arrests tied to attacks on federal property and threats against ICE personnel and facilities. [DHS]

How the law works
Prosecutors still charge arson, assault, explosives, conspiracy, and similar crimes. U.S. law defines domestic terrorism by the act and intent rather than membership in a named domestic group. [DOJ][FBI]

Where they have been most prominent

‚Ä¢ Washington. Tacoma ICE attack in 2019 and Seattle‚Äôs CHOP violence in 2020. [Seattle Police Blotter][Seattle Times]

‚Ä¢ Georgia. ‚ÄúStop Cop City‚Äù campaign with mass arrests under state domestic terrorism law. [GBI]

Bottom line
There is a multi year record of Antifa aligned individuals involved in arsons, assaults, and attacks on federal and civic targets. The White House now refers to Antifa as a domestic terrorist organization and has directed agencies to prioritize disruption and prosecution. [White House][DHS]
